[[Image:Early Rus.png|thumb|350px|Map showing [[Varangian]] or [[Rus' (people)|Rus']] settlement (in red) and location of Slavic tribes (in grey), mid-9th century [[Khazar]] influence indicated with blue outline]]

'''{{lang|non|Garðaríki}}''' (anglicized '''Gardariki''' or '''Gardarike''')<ref>[http://snl.no/Gardarike Store Norske Leksikon] (2005–2007)</ref> or '''{{lang|non|Garðaveldi}}''' is the [[Old Norse]] term used in [[Middle Ages|medieval times]] for the states of [[Kievan Rus']].

As the [[Varangians]] dealt mainly with Northern [[Rus' people|Rus']] lands, their [[saga]]s regard the city of {{lang|non|Holmsgardr|italic=no}} ({{lang|non|Holmgarðr}}, [[Veliky Novgorod]]) as the capital of {{lang|non|Garðaríki}}. Other local towns mentioned in the sagas are {{lang|non|Aldeigjuborg}} ([[Staraya Ladoga|Old Ladoga]]), {{lang|non|Kœnugarðr}} ([[Kiev]]), {{lang|non|Pallteskja}} ([[Polotsk]]), {{lang|non|Smaleskja}} ([[Smolensk]]), {{lang|non|Súrsdalar}} ([[Suzdal]]), {{lang|non|Móramar}} ([[Murom]]), and {{lang|non|Ráðstofa}} ([[Rostov]]).{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}

Three of the [[Varangian runestones]], [[Gotland Runic Inscription 114|G 114]], [[Södermanland Runic Inscription 338|Sö 338]], and [[Veda Runestone|U 209]], refer to Scandinavian men who had been in {{lang|non|Garðar}}.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Pritsak |first=Omeljan |authorlink=Omeljan Pritsak |title=The Origin of Rus': Old Scandinavian Sources Other than the Sagas |publisher=Harvard University Press |year=1981 |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts |pages=346, 396 |url= |isbn=0-674-64465-4}}</ref>

==Etymology==
The meaning of the word {{lang|non|Garðaríki}} is usually interpreted as {{wikt-lang|non|garðr}} + {{wikt-lang|non|ríki}}: "the kingdom of cities", or "the realm of towns",<ref name="penguin">''[http://us.penguingroup.com/nf/Book/BookDisplay/0,,9780141000039,00.html Sagas of the Icelanders]'', [[Penguin Group]]</ref> which probably referred to a chain of forts along the [[Volkhov River]], starting with [[Lyubsha]] and [[Staraya Ladoga|Ladoga]] (see [[Gord (archaeology)#Evolution of the word|Evolution of the word Gord]]). These forts had to assert themselves especially against the [[Khazars|Khazar Khaganate]] until the end of the 9th century and therefore they developed the first [[East Slavs|East Slavic]] state which is known as [[Kievan Rus']].

{{lang|non|Garðr}} contains the same root as Slavic {{lang|sla|[[grad (geography)|gord]]}} ("town") and [[English language|English]] ''garden''. {{lang|non|Garðr}} refers to a wall or fortification but came to primarily mean what it contained. For the [[Germanic languages|Germanic]] [[etymology]] of the latter element, see the article on {{lang|de|[[Reich]]}} and the archaic English term {{wikt-lang|ang|rike}}.

