'''Laguna Socompa''' is a small lake in the [[Salta Province]] of [[Argentina]], at the foot of [[Socompa]] volcano. It covers an area of about {{convert|200|ha}} and has an average depth of about {{convert|0.45|-|0.62|m}}. The lake is fed by [[arroyo (creek)|arroyos]] and [[spring (hydrology)|springs]], some of which are [[hot springs]]. Its waters are very rich in [[arsenic]] and otherwise salty and slightly alkaline; these properties and the regionally high [[UV radiation]] give Laguna Socompa extreme environmental conditions.

The lake features the highest known [[Stromatolite|stromatoliths]] known on Earth, these are structures formed by microorganisms; stromatoliths were the dominant lifeforms on Earth recorded between 3.5 and 1.5 billion years ago and may give insight on [[Earliest known life forms|early life on Earth]]. These stromatoliths are found on the southern shore of the lake and led to Laguna Socompa being declared a [[protected area]].

== Geography and geomorphology ==

Laguna Socompa is located at an elevation of {{convert|3570|m}}{{sfn|Rasuk|Ferrer|Kurth|Portero|2017|p=866}} in the [[Los Andes Department]] of the [[Salta Province]] in [[Argentina]], close to the border with [[Chile]]. A [[railway]] to the border with [[Chile]] passes east of Laguna Socompa; the Socompa [[railway station]] lies {{circa}} {{convert|10|km}} north-northwest of the lake and the Quebrada del Agua station northeast of the lake is even closer.{{sfn|Vides Almonacid|1990|p=118}} The area is far away from any city or town{{sfn|Farías|Rascovan|Toneatti|Albarracín|2013|p=2}} but [[sodium sulfate]] was produced in the area of Laguna Socompa.<ref name="Barrientos1998" /> The lake was defined a [[protected area]] in 2011<ref name="CONICET" /> but is also in the area of the Socompa [[geothermal power]] [[Prospecting|prospect]].{{sfn|Lelli|2018|p=23}}

The lake covers a surface of about {{convert|200|ha}}{{sfn|Vides Almonacid|1990|p=119}} and has the form of an "L" upside down and backwards. Its depth fluctuates between {{convert|0.45|-|0.62|m}}{{sfn|Vides Almonacid|1990|p=118}} with lower water levels during December to May.{{sfn|Farías|Rascovan|Toneatti|Albarracín|2013|p=2}} The northwestern and eastern shores feature well developed [[wetland]] vegetation{{sfn|Vides Almonacid|1990|p=118}} and are about {{convert|5|km}} long, while dry [[beach]]es are found elsewhere along the shore. Sandy-stony ground with [[bush (plant)|bush]] vegetation characterizes the surrounding landscape{{sfn|Vides Almonacid|1990|p=119}} which is in general mountainous.<ref name="Volante2012" /> Reportedly, the area of the lake smells of [[sulfur]].<ref name="Gil2018" />

Some [[arroyo (creek)|arroyos]] enter into Laguna Socompa,<ref name="CCdlP2018" /> and on the eastern side water flows from the Quebrada del Agua spring towards the lake; part of its water is piped to an old [[Mill (grinding)|mill]] at the railway. Additional [[Spring (hydrology)|springs]]{{sfn|Lelli|2018|p=6}} occur around{{sfn|Vides Almonacid|1990|p=119}} and within the lake. On the western-southwestern margins of the lake,{{sfn|Lelli|2018|p=6}} [[hot spring]]s with temperatures of up to {{convert|26|C}}{{sfn|Albarracín|Gärtner|Farias|2016|p=18}}-{{convert|27.5|C}} are found; volcanic activity represented by the Socompa volcano is responsible for heating the waters of the hot springs. The activity of the hot springs has resulted in the deposition of [[diatomite]]<ref name="Volante2012" /> and [[sodium sulfate]] along the shores.{{sfn|Lelli|2018|p=6}}

The waters of the lake are somewhat [[alkaline]],<ref name="AlbarracínKraiselburd2016" /> turbid, [[brackish]]{{sfn|Vides Almonacid|1990|p=118}} to [[hypersaline]]{{sfn|Albarracín|Gärtner|Farias|2016|p=18}} and have a high [[arsenic]] content.<ref name="Kurth2017" /> The lakefloor is covered by material with a composition resembling [[brine]], [[clay]] and [[silt]].{{sfn|Vides Almonacid|1990|p=119}} [[Oncolite]]s have also been reported from Laguna Socompa.<ref name="Rizzo2015" />

The lake is situated at the foot of the active volcano [[Socompa]]<ref name="AlbarracínKraiselburd2016" /> within a depression at its foot; the depression was formerly a north-northwest trendig valley{{sfn|van Wyk de Vries|Self|Francis|Keszthelyi|2001|p=227}} before the volcano grew in the valley.{{sfn|van Wyk de Vries|Self|Francis|Keszthelyi|2001|p=228}} The volcano features steaming ground and [[fumarole]]s at its summit.{{sfn|Lelli|2018|p=23}}

== Climate and environment ==

The lake is part of the cold, dry [[Altiplano|Puna]] where temperatures vary strongly between day and night and precipitation only occurs in summer.{{sfn|Vides Almonacid|1990|p=118}} In summer temperatures range between {{convert|20|-|-10|C}} and in winter they can drop to {{convert|10|-|-20|C}}.<ref name="Kurth2017" /> The region has the highest quantities of incoming solar radiation in the world, including the largest amount of [[UV radiation]].<ref name="Toneatti2017" />

The small lakes in the Puna desert are influenced by extreme environmental conditions such as large amounts of toxic elements such as [[arsenic]], high [[salinity]] and strong [[ultraviolet radiation]]<ref name="OrdoñezLanzarotti2013" /> as the [[ozone]] column is less dense at high elevations;{{sfn|Rasuk|Ferrer|Kurth|Portero|2017|p=866}} these lakes in general receive more [[insolation]] than any other place on Earth.{{sfn|Rasuk|Ferrer|Kurth|Portero|2017|p=865}} Because of the dry climate, most of the lakes lose water mainly through [[evaporation]] and thus tend to accumulate salt and arsenic.{{sfn|Albarracín|Gärtner|Farias|2016|p=15}}

== Biology ==

Small lakes in the Puna are places where [[bird]]s concentrate in comparison to the surrounding environments. About 27 bird species have been observed at Laguna Socompa, including both [[Water bird|waterbirds]] and terrestrial birds, the most common are ''[[Anas flavirostris]]'' (Yellow-billed teal), ''[[Hirundo rustica]]'' (Barn swallow), ''[[Larus seranus]]'', ''[[Lessonia rufa]]'' (Austral negrito) and ''[[Lophonetta specularioides]]'' (Crested duck).{{sfn|Vides Almonacid|1990|p=117}} Among mammals, [[vicuña]]s have been reported from Laguna Socompa.<ref name="Diaz2000" /> 

The vegetation in the wetlands around the lake is characterized by [[cyperaceae]] and [[graminaceae]].{{sfn|Vides Almonacid|1990|p=119}} Underwater vegetation does not occur in Laguna Socompa owing to the brackish water.{{sfn|Vides Almonacid|1990|p=126}} There is little [[phytoplankton]] in the lake waters, mainly [[cyanobacteria]] and [[diatom]]s.{{sfn|Farías|Rascovan|Toneatti|Albarracín|2013|p=2}}

=== Microorganisms ===

Microorganisms who live in the lakes and wetlands of the dry Andes have to resist harmful environmental traits{{sfn|Albarracín|Gärtner|Farias|2016|p=15}} and thus become extremely hardy with e.g high UV radiation tolerance. They often also produce [[secondary metabolite]]s that are of interest to the industry, such as [[medicine]], [[Sunscreen|UV blocking]] and [[bioremediation]],{{sfn|Rasuk|Ferrer|Kurth|Portero|2017|p=865}} which has spurned research in these extreme environments.{{sfn|Rasuk|Ferrer|Kurth|Portero|2017|p=866}} Furthermore, they are considered to be potential counterparts to [[extraterrestrial life]] in light of the environmental conditions.{{sfn|Albarracín|Gärtner|Farias|2016|p=14}}

Several microorganisms in the lake have been isolated and researched, with their [[genome sequencing|genomes sequenced]].<ref name="AlbarracínKraiselburd2016" /> Among these is ''[[Exiguobacterium]] sp.'' strain 17 which was first isolated in Laguna Socompa; its sequenced genome contains a number of genes involved in metabolizing arsenic and other toxic compounds and protecting and repairing the genome.<ref name="Farias2011" /><ref name="OrdoñezLanzarotti2013" /> Other strains from Laguna Socompa whose genome has been sequenced are ''[[Salinivibrio]] sp.'' strain 34 and 35.{{sfn|Albarracín|Gärtner|Farias|2016|p=23}}

=== Stromatoliths ===
[[File:Stromatolites Volcanic Lake.jpg|thumb|Photo of stromatoliths in Laguna Socompa]]
In 2009,<ref name="ElUniverso2009" /> researchers discovered the presence of [[Stromatolite|stromatoliths]] at Laguna Socompa;<ref name="Poiré2014" /> stromatoliths are layered structures formed by microorganisms when their metabolism causes the accumulation of minerals.<ref name="Toneatti2017" /> These are the first stromatoliths found in Argentina{{sfn|Rasuk|Ferrer|Kurth|Portero|2017|p=866}} and the highest site where stromatoliths have been recorded;<ref name="Toneatti2017" /> their existence was the reason why the lake was made a protected area.<ref name="CONICET" />

{{Life timeline}}
The discovery of stromatoliths at Laguna Socompa and the extreme conditions that exist there offers insights into the development of [[Earliest known life forms|early life on Earth]]{{sfn|Albarracín|Gärtner|Farias|2016|p=14}} as microbe-formed structures like stromatoliths were the main traces of life from between 3.5 and 1.5 billion years ago before stromatoliths declined between 1 and 0.7 billion years ago{{sfn|Farías|Rascovan|Toneatti|Albarracín|2013|p=1}} due to the increased presence of burrowing and grazing lifeforms at that time.<ref name="Toneatti2017" /> Previously stromatoliths were known mainly from marine and carbonatic environments such as in the [[Bahamas]], the [[Coorong National Park|Coorong Lagoon]] and [[Shark Bay]] in [[Australia]], the [[Lagoa Salgada]] in [[Brazil]] and the [[Laguna Bacalar]] in [[Mexico]]. The Laguna Socompa stromatoliths are the first to be discovered at elevations exceeding {{convert|3500|m}};<ref name="Poiré2014" /> the presence of active [[hot spring]]s may be responsible for their formation at Laguna Socompa.<ref name="HovlandRuesåtten2018" />

These stromatoliths have a layered structure and cone-like shapes that sometimes overlap and then form large domes,{{sfn|Farías|Rascovan|Toneatti|Albarracín|2013|p=2}} unlike the bushy or crustose stromatoliths found elsewhere,<ref name="Poiré2014" /> and are found underwater on the southern shores of the lake, protected from the strong UV radiation.{{sfn|Albarracín|Gärtner|Farias|2016|p=18}} They have a layered structure, with very different environments between the surfaces and the interiors of the individual stromatoliths.<ref name="Toneatti2017" /> The UV protective [[carotenoid]] pigment [[deinoxanthin]] gives them a pink colour.{{sfn|Albarracín|Gärtner|Farias|2016|p=21}} Unusually, some stromatoliths are formed out of [[halite]] rather than the more common [[aragonite]]/[[carbonate]]<ref name="Poiré2014" /> although aragonite and [[silica]] are their most important building materials.{{sfn|Albarracín|Gärtner|Farias|2016|p=18}}

The dominant bacteria in the stromatoliths are ''[[Microcoleus]]'' [[cyanobacteria]] and [[deinococci]] in the surface;{{sfn|Albarracín|Gärtner|Farias|2016|p=21}} there are also [[eukaryotic]] [[alga]]e, [[diatom]]s.<ref name="Albarracín2012" /> Other taxa include [[desulfobacterales]], [[rhodobacteraceae]] and [[spirochaetes]] and are mostly novel lineages of bacteria;<ref name="AlbarracínKraiselburd2016" /> the diversity of the lifeforms increases away from the surface and towards the interior of the stromatolith.<ref name="Toneatti2017" /> Some of the Laguna Socompa stromatoliths are classified as ''Conophyton'' stromatoliths, which are otherwise only known as [[Precambrian]] (over 541 ± 1 million years old<ref name="ICC2018" />) fossils.<ref name="Poiré2014" />

