{{For|the town of Selfoss near Reykjavík|Selfoss (town)}}
[[File:Selfoss July 2014.JPG|thumb|Selfoss in 2014]]
[[File:SelfossViewFromNorthEast.jpg|thumb]]
[[File:Selfoss-Waterfall-Iceland-06050027.jpg|thumb|The Waterfall Selfoss]]

'''Selfoss''' is a [[waterfall]] on the river [[Jökulsá á Fjöllum]] in the north of [[Iceland]].  The river drops over a number of waterfalls over about 30 km before flowing into Öxarfjörður, a bay of the Arctic Sea.<ref>{{cite web|title=Over the edge: Extreme kayakers who laugh in the face of the world's most powerful waterfalls|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2155371/Over-edge-Extreme-kayakers-dice-death-plummet-precipice-worlds-powerful-waterfalls.html|website=[[Daily Mail]]|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref> The river originates as melt water from the [[glacier]] [[Vatnajökull]] and therefore the water flow varies depending on the season, the weather and [[volcano|volcanic activity]].<ref name=NG>{{cite web|title=Sunrise on the Selfoss waterfall|url=http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/photo-contest/2011/entries/108425/view/|website=[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic Magazine]]|publisher=[[National Geographic Society]]|accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref> 

A few hundred meters downstream of the ''Selfoss'' waterfall ({{convert|11|m}} high), the [[Dettifoss]] waterfall is situated, the most powerful waterfall in [[Europe]]. The river falls {{convert|44|m}} over a width of {{convert|100|m}}. Below the falls, the river passes through a gorge which is part of the [[Jökulsárgljúfur National Park]].

